ay” and drove off</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In conversations with people ranging from taxi drivers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to car drivers, to bus drivers, many of them have a poor opinion of cyclists because we “get in the way”</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.43pt; padding-left:5.57pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Drivers don’t understand why cyclists often need to take an aggressive road position (e.g. centre of their lane on a roundabout), this makes the drive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rs aggressive towards the cyclists, despite the cyclists course of action being reasonable</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I have, on my bike, been doing over 30mph on a 30mph speed limit road, central position, keeping up with traffic ahead, then been overtaken and sworn at for having a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> central position. To overtake the driver had to cut directly in front of me in a dangerous way. The swearing is not usual but the attitude and driving style is the norm, and demonstrates a general lack of understanding about cycle safety (i.e. don’t want </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to be right next to parked cars, don’t want to be on the inside of fast moving traffic on a single lane when you are at the same speed, so take a central position providing you are at the same speed as traffic)</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Road setup is often poor</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.05pt; padding-left:4.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Segregated cycle lan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es where cyclists have priority equal or greater to cars are necessary in order to make them useable, as well as to build greater respect from car drivers. Amsterdam is not a safe cycling city because they are good cyclists (many of them are terribly unsaf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e), but because the road system acknowledges cyclists as more vulnerable and hence deserving of greater priority and protection. This leads to drivers treating cyclists with greater respect, as well as encouraging cycling by creating more useable paths. Ho</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">wever note whilst the good cycling system gives safety in particular places, the overall attitude towards cyclists makes cycling anywhere very safe</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Other countries achieve better cycling uptake and safety figures because the compromise on the experience fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r cars to improve cyclists experience</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.43pt; padding-left:5.57pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Elephant and castle roundabout (on a cycle superhighway) is extremely dangerous, particularly for those that are unexperienced</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Going down South towards Hyde Park corner has very fast traffic, many busses and taxis (so </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the bus lane offers no protection), and makes it impossible to turn right, or attempt any manoeuvre</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Often parking in cycle lanes</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.13pt; padding-left:6.87pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cycle lanes typically mix with traffic</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.95pt; padding-left:5.05pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Where cycle lanes don’t mix with traffic they often give minor roads priority over them </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">making them almost entirely useless to the utility cyclist that is interested in making good time (in these cases I will use the main road with the cars in preference)</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Segregated cycle lanes often put cyclists at greater risk by making them re-join traffic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> when it is not safe to do so without first stopping</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.3pt; padding-left:7.7pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cycle lanes are often put in without a clear purpose – beginning and ending at random in places that are completely impractical. The cycle superhighways in this sense are good</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.41pt; padding-left:7.59pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Some major roads will never</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be suitable for cyclists with current traffic levels, many vehicles pulling on. The barrier for cyclists is they must either use these busy roads of have to navigate many tricky twists and turns on minor roads. Making clear routes through quieter areas wo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uld help give a viable alternative to busy major roads</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cycle attitudes</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.05pt; padding-left:4.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are an increasing number of poor cyclists in London, with particular areas being bad for cyclists running red lights, further harming people’s attitudes towards cyclists</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many cycl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ists are now without helmets. However in Belgium/The Netherlands this is common and not an issue</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.43pt; padding-left:5.57pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“Fixie” cyclists are the worst offenders for running red lights, having no low gears to be able to start quickly they try to avoid stopping</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. These are very muc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h in fashion now</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I never see cyclists being punished for these offences, despite seeing several of them every single day. When I mention to people that they ran a red light I am faced with swearing and abuse instantly. When I elaborate to tell them my frie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd was killed in such an accident, and I was knocked off and sworn at because of the poor perception of cyclists, they are generally taken aback and apologise. This kind of education should be out there more. Cyclists don’t realise the impact their rule br</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eaking has on people’s perceptions</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Road rules</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.05pt; padding-left:4.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Road rules currently make no accommodation for cyclists compared to cars</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">From a common sense point of view it is clear that from a safety perspective there are often times when it is safe for a cyc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">list to go </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">through a red light, despite it still being illegal</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.43pt; padding-left:5.57pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These times include: Pedestrian lights after stopping when no-one is crossing, turning left on a red light, going straight on at a red light when there is a green light for traffic coming in from the righ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t (but not necessarily traffic taking advantage of the green light)</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Netherlands allows cyclists priority on roundabouts without them having to take a central position. Not suitable for very busy junctions but a helpful approach at times. Generally many</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> lessons to be learnt from others road setup</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>